  "prompt": "Knighthood: Is it possible for a non-native British citizen to be knighted?",
  "response": "Yes, it is possible for a non-native British citizen to be knighted. The British honors system allows for honorary knighthoods to be conferred upon individuals who are not citizens of the United Kingdom or the Commonwealth realms. These honorary knighthoods recognize significant contributions to society, culture, or international relations. Recipients of honorary knighthoods are entitled to use the post-nominal letters associated with the honor but do not receive the title \"Sir\" or \"Dame.\" If a recipient later becomes a British citizen, their honorary knighthood can be converted to a substantive knighthood, allowing them to use the title \"Sir\" or \"Dame.\"",
